defaultn addition, the WHO has started to address the related issues of human rights. Their QualityRights program aims to provide resources for monitoring mental health care facilities and supporting processes for improving the care they provide.
default5.1
default              
default Despite the 
defaultgrowing recognition of the essent
defaultial need to address psychosocial disabilities in development, global development budgets remain woefully inadequate. The UK Government, through DfID
default, is one of the few governments who have invested in understanding more about scaling up services for mental health in low resources settings. Since 2005
default,
default DfID have funded two Research Partnership Consortiums. The Mental Health and Poverty Project explored
default the relationship between poverty and mental health in four African countries. Since 2011, DfID have committed to funding £6 million over 6 years for the PRogramme for Improving Mental health care (PRIME).
default PRIME is groundbreaking as it is the first projec
defaultt to design, implement, scale up and evaluate mental health services in collaboration with Ministries of Health in five countries in Asia and Africa.
default5.2
default              
defaultAs DfID has taken a lead in commissioning appropriate research in this field, it is well placed to tra
defaultnslate this into scaled programmes. While there are few examples at present, the strength of evidence, and systematic way that DfID has approached this, is a good foundation on which to build. 
default6.1
default              
default Mental health is unique in its relevance to many other aspects of health and development. As well as being critical to success in addressing poverty and economic development, there are strong links to almost all the other Millennium Development Goa
defaultls.  Psychosocial disabilities are the most common Non-Communicable Diseases (NCD) by disease burden, as well as playing an important role in successful interventions for the other NCDs. In a similar way, there are key mental health aspects of programmes a
defaultddressing HIV/Aids (depression, medication compliance), maternal and child health (post-natal depression, early child stimulation) and Neglected Tropical Diseases (stigma, depression). 
default6.2
default              
default Mental health status is associated in multiple ways with each of 
defaultthe nine thematic areas for emerging post-MDG priorities, and can therefore be considered as a fully cross-cutting issue.  For instance, in relation to education, educational stressors are risk factors for college students, while an important route for acc
defaultess to mental health care for young people is via educational organizations.
default7
default.1 
default              
defaultTh
defaulte growing
default momentum 
defaultof evidence, advocacy networks and investment 
defaultis reflected in the increasingly strong policy and legislative framework for psychosocial disability. The CRPD has psychosocial disabilities as a core mandate, proving a strong mechanism for holding signatory countries to account. This monitoring function 
defaultis explicitly stated in the CRPD (Article 33(2)) as a key way that persons with psychosocial disabilities and the organizations can participate.  
default7
default.2
default              
defaultThe stigma associated with psychosocial disabilities has been such that their voice has been poorly repre
defaultsented even among the disability movement, let alone in the health and development sector.  This is changing fast, with increasing numbers of countries having organizations of persons with psychosocial disabilities, and in some cases continental umbrella b
defaultodies, such as the Pan African Network of Persons with Psychosocial Disabilities. This will allow greater participation in not only CRPD processes (e.g. parallel reports), but at all levels of service development and planning that affect their interests. G
defaultlobal development organizations and governments need to commit to this principle.
